ce:section.ce:para:
Undoubtedly, Lee et al. work was very much exciting but limited to study of dispersion of CIS-ZnS QDs in NLCs only [56] but not explored in other types of LCs for a while. Being inspired from Lee et al. work, Singh et al. tried the doping of CIS-ZnS QDs into FLC (Felix 17/000) in search of their much sought applications in electro-optical, solar cells and energy storing devices [57]. CIS-ZnS QDs (~6.5 nm) were synthesized by using chemical route [58]. The polarising optical micrographs of the mixtures (0.25, 0.5 and 1.0 wt%) and neat sample in three LC phases (SmC*, SmA* and N*) clearly shows that ordering of LC molecules gets disturbed and strongly concentration-dependent (Fig. 5
                        ). However, just to mention that authors limited their investigations to SmC* phase only. Two main order parameters i.e. tilt angle (θ, primary) and spontaneous polarization (PS, secondary) of SmC* phase was greatly impacted by dispersed CIS-ZnS QDs. Both order parameters were found to significantly decrease in the mixtures as compared to neat sample (Fig. 6
                        ) and the theoretically fitted equation explaining the exponential decrease in both parameters was proposed. Authors believed that the adverse flexoelectric polarization might be playing major role in reduction of tilt angle and PS.

In extension to their studies, Doke et al. also reported the achievement of sustained multiferroic behavior with the intrinsic ferroelectric nature by employing the ferroelectric (P-E) and ferromagnetic (M-H) hysteresis loop studies [66]. The P-E measurements clearly showed the hysteresis loop in pure FLC (KCFLC 7S) and CZZ QDs-FLC composites [Fig. 11
                        ] and could be utilized for memory devices. The saturation electric polarization (PS) of the composites evaluated from P-E loop was found to increase with increase in Co concentration in CZZ QDs. This could be due to the larger dipole moment of Co which constructively interferes with FLC dipoles and hence with increase in Co concentration, the PS of the composite would eventually increase. The similar results on CZZ QDs-FLC composites were also obtained with M-H measurements i.e. saturation magnetization (MS) increases with increase in Co concentration of CZZ QDs. Moreover, authors measured the helical pitch in pure FLC and their composites with CZZ QDs [Fig. 12
                        ] and found that it remained more or less same. This again confirmed that dispersion of CZZ QDs (size almost similar to FLC molecule) into FLC did not perturb its ferroelectric nature. Authors pointed out that neither the magnetic vector of QDs and nor the director of host FLC sample disturb the intrinsic nature of FLC sample and QDs, respectively. This probably led to simultaneous increment in ferroelectric and ferromagnetic ordering in the composites and eventually resulted into the sustained multiferroic behaviour of CZZ QDs-FLC composites. In nutshell, these Cd-free core/shell QDs-LC mixtures are potential candidates for the next-generation QDs based LCDs that exploit both electric and magnetic data storage inside it.

In recent years, highly luminescent carbon dots (CDs) are emerged as mystic nanomaterial with magical physical and chemical properties together with biocompatibilities. CDs have been acknowledged as good replacement for Cd based QDs because of their high quantum yield, photostability, low toxicity, water solubility, good conductivity, and eco-friendly nature. Taking such fascinating physical and optical properties of CDs, Shukla et al. [71] dispersed CDs in a phenylpyrimidine-based FLC material at concentrations (~ 0.05 to 0.10 wt%) and studied their effect on the electro-optical and dielectric properties of FLC sample. The phase transition temperatures and tilt angle (Fig. 18
                        (a)) of FLC present in QDs-FLC composites were not much impacted by CDs. However, the enhancement in switching response time (τ) and spontaneous polarization (PS) was found to be ~ 31% and 15% in the 0.10 wt% composites, respectively (Fig. 18(b) and (c)). Authors mentioned that the enhancement in τ could be due to: (i) increase in rotational viscosity and conductivity of FLC and (ii) no impact of impurity ions and localized electric field. The dielectric constant (ε′), dielectric loss (ε″) and dielectric anisotropy (Δε) were also increased in the composites as compared to neat FLC sample. The ac conductivity of FLC sample was also enhanced by CDs (Fig. 19
                        ). As seen in the graph, in low frequency regime no significant changes in conductivity are observed but enhancement is present in higher frequency range. This could be due to higher conductivity of CDs and the contributions from ITO. The significant increment in dielectric parameters and spontaneous polarization was attributed to the (i) parallel coupling between the FLC diploes and CDs and (ii) one order increase in dc conductivity (evaluated from ac conductivity). The relaxation frequency corresponding to the Goldstone mode in FLC was suppressed by CDs. Such reduction in the relaxation was attributed to the modification in the rotational viscosity of Goldstone mode and increase in dc conductivity. Authors were successful in demonstrating that because of the unique properties of CDs, the electro-optical and dielectric results obtained for CDs-FLC were contrary to those obtained from other carbon-based nanomaterial-FLC mixtures.

Study of dispersion of CDs in LC media is still in a rudimentary stage of evolution. In a quest to further explore the effect of CDs on the dielectric properties of FLCs, Gangwar et al. reported dispersion of CDs (~4.5 nm) into FLC (KCFLC 10S) matrix [72]. To investigate the dielectric properties, authors prepared three distinct sample cells: (i) S1 (strong rubbing of a Nylon 6/6 coated substrates), (ii) S2 (CDs (5 wt%) dispersed FLC composites), and (iii) S3 (CDs deposited on strongly rubbed Nylon 6/6 coated substrates). At room temperature, the measuring ac voltage-dependent dielectric constant (ε′) and dielectric loss factor (tanδ) were recorded on S1, S2, and S3 sample cells (Fig. 20
                        ). In pure FLC sample (S1), ε′ increases with increase of measuring voltage and becomes maximum at 300 mV and such increment is indicative of existence of more than one relaxation as observed in tanδ graph (Fig. 20(a) and (b)). The relaxation corresponding to higher frequency is well-known Goldstone mode, whereas new relaxation at lower frequency is related to partially unbound helical mode (p-UHM), recently discovered by Biradar's group. It was confirmed that increment in ε′ upto 300 mV is due to the contribution of p-UHM. The relaxation frequency of p-UHM was found to increase with increase in probing voltage further confirming the partial unwinding of a helicoidal structure at the interface of FLC and the substrate surface of the sample cell. Dielectric measurements done on S2 and S3 samples clearly showed that ε′ reduced to almost half of the S1 sample with minute increment in its value (Fig. 20(c) and (e)). Only one relaxation peak corresponding to the Goldstone mode (independent of amplitude of ac measuring voltage) in tanδ plots was seen in both S2 and S3 samples, which clearly excludes the possibility of p-UHM (Fig. 20(d) and (f)). Authors pointed out that the p-UHM fully suppressed in both cases i.e. CDs present in the bulk of FLC (S2 sample cell) and CDs deposited on the substrate surface and remained between solid substrate surface and FLC sample (S3 sample cell). To cross-check the presence of p-UHM throughout the SmC* phase and in the vicinity of Tc of SmC*-SmA* phase transition, temperature dependent dielectric measurements were performed in S2 and S3 samples and compared with S1 sample. However, p-UHM was not detected in both S2 and S3 samples confirming that CDs completely suppressed it. Temperature-dependent relaxation frequency of Goldstone mode was significantly larger in S3 and S2 samples as compared to S1 sample. It was mentioned that the shift in relaxation frequency was higher in S3 sample due to the tight binding of FLC molecules at the substrate surface as compared to the bulk molecules. Moreover, the high-resolution optical textures and contact angle results corroborate well with dielectric results i.e. CDs suppresses the p-UHM in both S2 and S3 sample cells. Authors also proposed a model for the helicoidal structure in the pure FLC sample (S1), CDs dispersed in bulk of FLC (S2) and CDs deposited on Nylon coated substrates (S3) to explain the absence of p-UHM in S2 and S3 sample cells (Fig. 21
                        ). Authors were able to reveal the impact of CDs on the partially unwound helical structure at the interface of FLC and solid substrate. These studies made by authors would help in enriching the science behind the CDs-FLC interactions.
